    "message_1": "Suppose we have a dataset with two classes, labeled 0 and 1, and two predictor variables, x1 and x2. By using discriminant analysis, determine the boundary equation (in the form of ax1 + bx2 + c = 0) that can be used to classify new observations.\n\nClass 0: {(1, 6), (2, 5), (3, 7), (4, 10)}\nClass 1: {(3, 2), (4, 3), (5, 1), (6, 3)}\n\nUse a prior probability of 0.5 for each class.",
    "message_2": "To perform linear discriminant analysis, we first need to calculate the mean vectors for each class, the covariance matrix, and the inverse of the covariance matrix.\n\nMean vectors for each class:\nClass 0: μ0 = ( (1+2+3+4)/4 , (6+5+7+10)/4 ) = (2.5, 7)\nClass 1: μ1 = ( (3+4+5+6)/4 , (2+3+1+3)/4 ) = (4.5, 2.25)\n\nCovariance matrix:\nFirst, we calculate the deviation matrices for each class:\nClass 0: \n[\n(1-2.5, 6-7),\n(2-2.5, 5-7),\n(3-2.5, 7-7),\n(4-2.5, 10-7)\n]\n=>\n[\n(-1.5, -1),\n(-0.5, -2),\n(0.5, 0),\n(1.5, 3)\n]\n\nClass 1:\n[\n(3-4.5, 2-2.25),\n(4-4.5, 3-2.25),\n(5-4.5, 1-2.25),\n(6-4.5, 3-2.25)\n]\n=>\n[\n(-1.5, -0.25),\n(-0.5, 0.75),\n(0.5, -1.25),\n(1.5, 0.75)\n]\n\nNow, we calculate the covariance matrices for each class:\nCov0 = (1/(4-1)) * (Σ (deviation0 * deviation0.T))\nCov1 = (1/(4-1)) * (Σ (deviation1 * deviation1.T))\n\nCov0 = \n[\n(1/3) * ((-1.5)^2 + (-0.5)^2 + (0.5)^2 + (1.5)^2), (1/3) * ((-1.5)*(-1) + (-0.5)*(-2) + (0.5)*(0) + (1.5)*(3)),\n(1/3) * ((-1)*(-1.5) + (-2)*(-0.5) + (0)*(0.5) + (3)*(1.5)), (1/3) * ((-1)^2 + (-2)^2 + (0)^2 + (3)^2)\n]\n=>\n[\n(1.5, 1.5),\n(1.5, 3)\n]\n\nCov1 = \n[\n(1/3) * ((-1.5)^2 + (-0.5)^2 + (0.5)^2 + (1.5)^2), (1/3) * ((-1.5)*(-0.25) + (-0.5)*(0.75) + (0.5)*(-1.25) + (1.5)*(0.75)),\n(1/3) * ((-0.25)*(-1.5) + (0.75)*(-0.5) + (-1.25)*(0.5) + (0.75)*(1.5)), (1/3) * ((-0.25)^2 + (0.75)^2 + (-1.25)^2 + (0.75)^2)\n]\n=>\n[\n(1.5, 0.5),\n(0.5, 1)\n]\n\nNow, we calculate the pooled covariance matrix:\nCov_pooled = (1/2) * (Cov0 + Cov1)\n=>\n[\n(1/2) * (1.5 + 1.5), (1/2) * (1.5 + 0.5),\n(1/2) * (1.5 + 0.5), (1/2) * (3 + 1)\n]\n=>\n[\n(1.5, 1),\n(1, 2)\n]\n\nNow, we calculate the inverse of the pooled covariance matrix:\nCov_pooled_inv = \n[\n(2, -1),\n(-1, 1.5)\n]\n\nNow, we can calculate the boundary equation coefficients:\na = (μ1 - μ0) * Cov_pooled_inv\n=>\n[\n(4.5 - 2.5, 2.25 - 7)\n]\n*\n[\n(2, -1),\n(-1, 1.5)\n]\n=>\n[\n(2, -4.75)\n]\n*\n[\n(2, -1),\n(-1, 1.5)\n]\n=>\n(2*2 + (-4.75)*(-1), 2*(-1) + (-4.75)*1.5)\n=>\n(4 + 4.75, -2 - 7.125)\n=>\n(8.75, -9.125)\n\nb = -0.5 * (μ1 * Cov_pooled_inv * μ1.T - μ0 * Cov_pooled_inv * μ0.T)\n=>\n-0.5 * (\n(4.5*2 + 2.25*(-1))*(4.5) + (2.5*2 + 7*(-1))*(2.5)\n)\n=>\n-0.5 * (\n(9 - 2.25)*4.5 + (5 - 7)*2.5\n)\n=>\n-0.5 * (\n(6.75)*4.5 + (-2)*2.5\n)\n=>\n-0.5 * (\n30.375 - 5\n)\n=>\n-0.5 * 25.375\n=>\n-12.6875\n\nSo, the boundary equation is:\n8.75x1 - 9.125x2 - 12.6875 = 0"
